  "prompt": "Why do I have red itchy balls all over my skin?",
  "response": "Having red, itchy bumps or rashes on your skin can be caused by a variety of factors. Here are some possible causes:\n\n### 1. **Allergic Reaction**\n   - **Cause**: Exposure to allergens like certain foods, medications, insect bites, or skincare products.\n   - **Symptoms**: Red, itchy bumps or hives that may appear suddenly.\n   - **Action**: Identify and avoid the allergen. Over-the-counter antihistamines like Benadryl can help.\n\n### 2. **Contact Dermatitis**\n   - **Cause**: Direct contact with irritants like soaps, detergents, plants (e.g., poison ivy), or chemicals.\n   - **Symptoms**: Red, itchy, and sometimes blistering rash in the area of contact.\n   - **Action**: Wash the area with soap and water, apply hydrocortisone cream, and avoid the irritant.\n\n### 3. **Heat Rash (Miliaria)**\n   - **Cause**: Blocked sweat ducts due to hot and humid weather or tight clothing.\n   - **Symptoms**: Small red bumps that may itch or feel prickly, often in areas prone to sweating.\n   - **Action**: Keep the skin cool and dry, wear loose clothing, and use calamine lotion.\n\n### 4. **Eczema (Atopic Dermatitis)**\n   - **Cause**: A chronic skin condition that causes inflammation and irritation.\n   - **Symptoms**: Red, itchy, and dry patches of skin that may flare up periodically.\n   - **Action**: Moisturize regularly, avoid triggers, and use prescribed creams or ointments.\n\n### 5. **Insect Bites**\n   - **Cause**: Bites from mosquitoes, fleas, bedbugs, or other insects.\n   - **Symptoms**: Red, itchy bumps, often in clusters or lines.\n   - **Action**: Apply anti-itch creams (e.g., hydrocortisone) and avoid scratching to prevent infection.\n\n### 6. **Fungal Infection**\n   - **Cause**: Fungal infections like ringworm or yeast infections.\n   - **Symptoms**: Red, itchy, and sometimes scaly patches that may spread.\n   - **Action**: Use antifungal creams or ointments and keep the area clean and dry.\n\n### 7. **Viral Infections**\n   - **Cause**: Viral illnesses like chickenpox or measles.\n   - **Symptoms**: Red, itchy spots or blisters, often accompanied by other symptoms like fever.\n   - **Action**: Consult a healthcare provider for proper diagnosis and treatment.\n\n### 8. **Stress or Anxiety**\n   - **Cause**: Stress can sometimes trigger or worsen skin conditions.\n   - **Symptoms**: Itchy, red patches or hives.\n   - **Action**: Practice stress management techniques and consider speaking with a healthcare provider.\n\n### When to See a Doctor\nConsult a healthcare provider if:\n- The rash spreads or worsens.\n- You experience severe itching, pain, or discomfort.\n- The rash is accompanied by fever, swelling, or difficulty breathing.\n- Over-the-counter treatments don\u2019t improve the condition.\n\nA healthcare professional can provide an accurate diagnosis and recommend appropriate treatment.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
